<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911205-0027</DOCNO><DOCID>911205-0027.</DOCID><HL>   Rite Aid Corp. Boosts   Its Offer to Purchase   Assets of Revco D.S.</HL><DATE>12/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12</SO><CO>   ECK RAD RDS</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)DRUG-BASED RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, PHARMACIES (RTD)ALL SPECIALTY RETAILERS (RTS)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>FLORIDA (FL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)OHIO (OH)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   SHIREMANSTOWN, Pa.  -- Rite Aid Corp. sweetened its offerfor the assets of Revco D.S., one day before a bankruptcycourt is scheduled to review proposals for the drugstorechain.   The revised proposal, submitted to U.S. Bankruptcy Courtin Akron, Ohio, would give holders of about $1.5 billion inRevco debt about $542 million in cash and 7.4 million RiteAid shares currently valued at about $131 million, for atotal of $673 million. As part of the plan, Revco's bankswould receive $248.5 million, a $28 million increase from theprevious offer, and subordinated debenture holders would get$50 million in cash in addition to the 4.5 million Rite Aidshares previously offered.</LP><TEXT>   Rite Aid, also a drugstore operator and specialtyretailer, in October offered a total of $585 million in cashand shares to take Twinsburg, Ohio-based Revco out of Chapter11 proceedings. That offer included $440 million in cash tosenior creditors and about seven million shares to juniorcreditors.   In late New York Stock Exchange trading yesterday, RiteAid shares were quoted at $17.875 each, down 25 cents.   Two other plans of reorganization are before thebankruptcy court. One has been submitted by Jack EckerdCorp., a closely held Clearwater, Fla., retailer anddrugstore operator, and the other by a creditor group.Revco's management previously indicated it supported thecreditor group's plan.   Revco, taken private in 1986, was one of the firstleveraged buy-outs to wind up in bankruptcy court.</TEXT></DOC>